{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638500"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17713"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10427"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77986"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10427"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63418"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10408"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24353"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77986"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman reports that the smell of freshly baked bread instantly reminds her of visiting her grandparent\u0027s house as a child, triggering vivid memories and feelings of happiness. She wonders why smells can evoke such strong emotional responses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of the limbic system in olfactory processing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Determines odour threshold sensitivity","Processes emotional and memory associations of odours","Controls olfactory receptor adaptation","Generates conscious smell perception","Filters irrelevant olfactory stimuli"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elimbic system processes emotional and memory associations of odours\u003C/strong\u003E via neural pathways connecting the amygdala with the hippocampus, which enables odours to evoke powerful emotional memories.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetermining odour threshold sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is handled by the olfactory epithelium\u0027s receptors, not limbic structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControlling olfactory receptor adaptation\u003C/strong\u003E happens within the olfactory epithelium through molecular mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerating conscious smell perception\u003C/strong\u003E requires integration of multiple brain regions beyond just the limbic system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFiltering irrelevant olfactory stimuli\u003C/strong\u003E is accomplished through inhibitory circuits in the olfactory bulb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOlfaction differs from other senses because signals travel directly to limbic areas without thalamic relay, enabling immediate emotional responses to smells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The piriform cortex, amygdala, and entorhinal cortex comprise the primary olfactory cortex and receive signals directly from the olfactory bulb.","Emotional and memory components of olfaction are processed via limbic system pathways between the amygdala and hippocampus.","Unlike other senses, olfactory signals do not pass through the thalamus before reaching the cortex."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63418"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17713"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63418"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T21:40:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T21:41:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10427"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77986"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{